<subSubSection id="B5E06557FFB4BA6F6CAA052BFEAB2912" pageId="7" pageNumber="143" type="description">
<paragraph id="FD4536DCFFB4BA6F6CAA052BFD8B2BCE" blockId="7.[151,1437,258,895]" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis id="CF8EEACEFFB4BA6F6CAA052BFEC02B86" bold="true" box="[199,381,366,391]" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">Measurements.</emphasis>
Head length (1.4); head width (2.5); pronotum length (2.5); pronotum width (6.0); scutellum length (4.9); scutellum width (3.6); length of antennal segments (I: 0.7; II: 1.0; III: 1.0; IV: 1.5; V missing); total length (11.6); abdominal width (6.6).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD4536DCFFB4BA6F6CAA059FFC8128A6" blockId="7.[151,1437,258,895]" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis id="CF8EEACEFFB4BA6F6CAA059FFE862BF2" bold="true" box="[199,315,474,499]" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">Diagnose.</emphasis>
Pronotum rugose. Arms of the anterior bifurcation of the metasternal process clavate (
<figureCitation id="65C12A59FFB4BA6F6945059FFA322BF2" box="[1320,1423,474,499]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[230,1378,230,1829]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[200,1387,193,1938]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. A – D. Edessa rugulata sp. n.: A – C, pygophore in dorsal, ventral and posterior view, respectively; D, metasternal process. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/545756/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">Fig. 4 D</figureCitation>
); excavation short receiving part of the fourth rostral segment. Peritreme reaching 1/3 of the distance between ostiole of the scent gland and lateral margin of the body (
<figureCitation id="65C12A59FFB4BA6F6E9A0667FCDF283A" box="[759,866,546,571]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[212,1372,254,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[200,1387,193,1938]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. A – E. Peritreme: A, Edessa viridula sp. n.; B, Edessa exigusternata sp. n.; C, Edessa angusticlada sp. n.; D, Edessa rugulata sp. n.; E, Edessa eucnema sp. n.. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/545760/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">Fig. 8 D</figureCitation>
). Evaporatorium with a long and raised crest in mesopleuron delimited by sulci; contiguous margin of meso and metapleuron also raised; metapleuron with two distinct raised crests one short medial and the other long distal. Spiracles concolorous with ventral surface. Trichobothria in yellowish calli. Antennae and legs spotless.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD4536DCFFB4BA6F6CAA06F7FEAB2912" blockId="7.[151,1437,258,895]" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis id="CF8EEACEFFB4BA6F6CAA06F7FEB928CA" bold="true" box="[199,260,690,715]" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="65C12A59FFB4BA6F6D7906F7FE2628CA" box="[276,411,690,715]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[230,1378,230,1829]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[200,1387,193,1938]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. A – D. Edessa rugulata sp. n.: A – C, pygophore in dorsal, ventral and posterior view, respectively; D, metasternal process. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/545756/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">Figs 4 A–C</figureCitation>
). Superior process of the genital cup reduced to a black line. Ventral part of the paramere with one barely distinct and rounded lateral lobe, base barely wider than distal part; lobes not distinctly projected posteriorly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B5E06557FFB4BA6F6CAA075BFC1B295B" pageId="7" pageNumber="143" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FD4536DCFFB4BA6F6CAA075BFC1B295B" blockId="7.[151,1437,258,895]" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis id="CF8EEACEFFB4BA6F6CAA075BFEF22936" bold="true" box="[199,335,798,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="143">Comments.</emphasis>
Female unknown. This species is very similar to the others has the shortest peritreme ruga in the group and is the only one with claviform arms of metasternal process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
